{{Western Buddhism}}
[[Image:Mahabodhitemple.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Mahabodhi|Mahabodhi temple]] in [[Bodhgaya]], [[India]]]]
'''Anagarika Shri Munindra''' (1915 – October 14, 2003), also called '''Munindraji''' by his disciples,<ref name="tricycle">{{cite web|title=In Memoriam: Anagarika Munindra (1914-2003) |url=http://www.tricycle.com/memoriam/memoriam-anagarika-munindra-1914-2003|publisher=[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review]]|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> was a [[Bengali people|Bengali]] [[vipassana]] meditation teacher, who taught many notable meditation teachers including [[Dipa Ma]],{{sfn |Schmidt|2005|p=11}}[[Joseph Goldstein (writer)|Joseph Goldstein]],{{sfn |Schmidt|2005|p=11}} [[Sharon Salzberg]],{{sfn |Schmidt|2005|p=9}} and [[Surya Das]].{{sfn |Das|2015|p=49}} [[Anagarika]] simply means a practicing Buddhist who leads a nomadic life without attachment in order to focus on the [[dharma]]. 

==Early life==
Anagarika was born in [[Chittagong, Bangladesh]] and descended from Buddhists of India forced east by the [[India#Medieval India|eleventh century Muslim invasion]].<ref name="tricycle"/>

==Buddhist Life==
He was an active member of the [[Maha Bodhi Society]]<ref name="tricycle"/> whose purpose was the resuscitation of Buddhism in India and the restoration of ancient Buddhist shrines there. Munindra was the superintendent of the [[Mahabodhi Temple]] at [[Bodh Gaya]] from 1953 to 1957,<ref name="tricycle"/> the first Buddhist to hold this position in modern times.  From 1957 to 1966 he lived in Burma, where he was a close disciple of [[Mahasi Sayadaw]],<ref name="tricycle"/> who authorized him to teach vipassana meditation.  While in Burma he also studied the [[Pali canon]] thoroughly,{{sfn|Knaster|2010|p=xiii}} before returning to India, where he taught vipassana for many years in [[Bodh Gaya]].{{sfn|Knaster|2010|p=xv}} He was known to be very open-minded and relaxed in the way he taught.{{sfn|Knaster|2010|p=x}} He would encourage his students to study with other teachers, and investigate other traditions.{{sfn|Knaster|2010|p=xvi}}

==In the tradition of Ledi Sayadaw==
During his stay in Burma he came in close contact with [[S. N. Goenka]] and had dhamma discussions with him.{{sfn|Knaster|2010|p=xvii}} Subsequently, he wished to learn Vipassana from Sayagyi U [[Ba Khin]] but since he had already learnt Vipassana from a monk, Sayagyi expressed his inability to teach him Vipassana in the tradition of [[Ledi Sayadaw]].<ref>{{cite web|title=My Friend, Munindraji By S. N. Goenka|url=http://www.vridhamma.org/en2004-09|publisher=Vipassana Research Institute|date=August 30, 2004|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref>

Finally, his wish was fulfilled a few years later when [[S. N. Goenka]] started teaching Vipassana in India. Munindra joined a 10-day course conducted by Goenka at Bodhgaya. He was very impressed by the technique, as expressed in a letter of appreciation that he wrote to Sayagyi U [[Ba Khin]] after the course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pariyatti.com/downloads/treasures/Maha_Bodhi_Journal_1972-04.pdf|title=The Maha Bodhi|page=91|date=April 1972|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref>

== Final years ==
He spent the last part of his life living at the Vipassana Research Institute's main meditation centre, Dhamma Giri, at the village of [[Igatpuri]], India, as a guest of his close friend [[S. N. Goenka]].{{sfn|Knaster|2010|p=xvii}}

