{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}
'''Charodi''' (also referred to as '''Mestha''', '''Achari''') are a community from the [[States and union territories of India|State]] of [[Karnataka]] in India. They are usually called as '''Mestha''' in North and South Karnataka.<ref name="b">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=lBRuUqydO8eBrQequoCYCw&id=sbO1AAAAIAAJ&dq=i+konkani&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=|title=Karnataka State gazetteer, Volume 13|publisher=Printed by the Director of Print, Stationery and Publications at the Govt. Press|year=1973|page=101}}</ref> Their traditional work is carpentry and work as carpenters.<ref name=a/><ref name=b/> They are included in [[other backward class|Other Backward Class]] (OBC) in the state of Karnataka.<ref name=c/><ref>[http://ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/karnataka.pdf "Central list of OBCs for the state of Karnataka"]</ref> 

Charodis are believed to have migrated from [[Goa]] in four boats ('char' means four and 'hodi' means boat) which landed in four different places of Karnataka. They were initially known as "Mestha" and after migration, they seemed to have changed their names based on the location they landed. They are known to be [[Vishwakarma (caste)|Vishwakarmas]] from [[Goa]]. They as per their tales, have migrated from [[Goa]] via sea-route to coastal Karnataka.<ref name="a">{{cite book|title=Karnataka by Kumar Suresh Singh, B. G. Halbar|year=2003|publisher=Anthropological Survey of India|pages=384–389|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxMwAQAAIAAJ&q=%22CharoDI&dq=%22CharoDI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=RRJuUvv9M8jarAfc_IFg&ved=0CEQQ6AEwBA}}</ref><ref name="b" /> During [[British Raj]] they were included among [[Denotified Tribes|criminal tribes]] of India.<ref name="c">{{cite book|title=A socio-history of ex-criminal communities OBCs by Shyam Singh Shashi, P. S. Varma|year=1991|publisher=Sundeep Prakashan|page=188|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=irXkAAAAMAAJ&q=Charodi+community&dq=Charodi+community&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jRJuUtyGNsTmrAe3poCwAg&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAw}}</ref> They are generally followers of [[Matha]].<ref name="b" /> They are also worshipers of [[Shiva]].

