[[File:Kernos Melos Sevres 3552.jpg|thumb|[[Terracotta]] ''kernos'' from the [[Cycladic art|Cycladic period]] (''ca.'' 2000 BC), found at [[Melos]]]]
[[File:NAMA Mystères d'Eleusis.jpg|thumb|In this votive plaque depicting elements of the [[Eleusinian Mysteries]], a female figure ''(top center of rectangular portion)'' wears a ''kernos'' on her head]]

In the [[Typology of Greek vase shapes|typology of ancient Greek pottery]], the '''''kernos''''' (Greek κέρνος or κέρχνος, plural ''kernoi'') is a pottery ring or stone tray to which are attached several small vessels for holding offerings. Its unusual design is described in literary sources, which also list the ritual ingredients it might contain.<ref>Jacquelyn Collins-Clinton, A Late Antique Shrine of Liber Pater at Cosa (Brill, 1976), pp. 29 –30 [https://books.google.com/books?id=CsoUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA30&dq=kernos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=8#v=onepage&q=kernos&f=false online.]</ref> The ''kernos'' was used primarily in the cults of [[Demeter]] and [[Persephone|Kore]], and of [[Cybele]] and [[Attis]].<ref>Phillippe Borgeaud, ''Mother of the Gods: From Cybele to the Virgin Mary'' (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1996, English translation 2004), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y9O96bVwwKkC&pg=PA113&dq=kernos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=10#v=onepage&q=kernos&f=false ''passim''.]</ref>

The Greek term is sometimes applied to similar compound vessels from other cultures found in the [[Mediterranean Basin|Mediterranean]], the [[Levant]], [[Mesopotamia]], and [[South Asia]].<ref>''Excavations at Mohenjo Daro, Pakistan: The Pottery'' (University of Pennsylvania Museum, 1986), p. 226 [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iew_THp8foC&pg=PA226&dq=kernos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=2#v=onepage&q=kernos&f=false  online.]</ref>

==Literary description==
[[Athenaeus]] preserves an ancient description of the ''kernos'' as

{{cquote|a [[terracotta]] vessel with many little bowls stuck on to it. In them there is sage, white poppy heads, wheat, barley, peas (?), vetches (?), pulse, lentils, beans, spelt (?), oats, cakes of compressed fruit, honey, olive oil, wine, milk, and unwashed sheep's wool. When one has carried this vessel, like a ''[[liknon|liknophoros]]'', he tastes of the contents.<ref>[[Athenaeus]] 11.478c = Polemon, frg. 88 Preller; English translation from Homer A. Thompson, ''Hellenistic Pottery and Terracottas'' (American School of Classical Studies at Athens, 1987), p. 448 [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ec8ejUxhfVwC&pg=PA148&dq=kernos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=9#v=onepage&q=kernos&f=false online.]</ref>}}

The ''kernos'' was carried in procession at the [[Eleusinian Mysteries]] atop the head of a priestess, as can be found depicted in art. A lamp was sometimes placed in the middle of a stationary ''kernos''.<ref>The verb ''kernophorein'' means "to bear the ''kernos''"; the noun for this is ''kernophoria''; Stephanos Xanthoudides, "Cretan Kernoi," ''Annual of the British School at Athens'' 12 (1906), p. 9.</ref>

